INDICATIONS:  38-year-old man with transaminitis. 
COMPARISONS:  None. 
TECHNIQUE:  Abdominal ultrasound examination. 
FINDINGS:  The gallbladder appears normal without cholelithiasis.  The common duct is not dilated.  The echotexture of the liver is diffusely hyperechoic consistent with fatty infiltration.  The main portal vein demonstrates normal hepatopetal flow. The right kidney measures 12.8 cm in length, the left 13.5 cm. Both kidneys appear normal without mass, hydronephrosis, or nephrolithiasis. The pancreas and spleen are unremarkable without splenomegaly. The spleen measures 10.1 cm in length. The caliber of the abdominal aorta is normal throughout the abdomen. There is no ascites. 
IMPRESSION: Echogenic liver consistent with fatty infiltration.  However, other forms of liver disease and more advanced liver disease, including significant hepatic fibrosis/cirrhosis cannot be excluded on this study.

INDICATION:  Evaluate for pneumothorax after chest tube removal. 
COMPARISON:  Comparison is made to film performed nine hours earlier same day. 
AP CHEST RADIOGRAPH: 
There has been interval removal of right-sided chest tube.  Moderate-to- large sized right pneumothorax is now seen, larger than prior study.  There is approximately 2.7 cm separation of lung apex from the chest wall.  There is also a moderate basilar component to the pneumothorax.  Cardiac and mediastinal contours appear relatively unchanged.  Normally midline mediastinal structures have not shifted significantly.  Left lung appears clear. 
IMPRESSION:  New moderate-to-large right-sided pneumothorax with apical and basilar components.  Findings discussed with Dr. [**First Name8 (NamePattern2) 4062**] [**Last Name (NamePattern1) 7173**] at 8:15 p.m. on [**2148-5-10**].

HISTORY:  Cognitive decline and difficulty swallowing. 
Contiguous axial images were obtained through the brain.  Imaging was performed before and during intravenous administration of 100 cc of Optiray contrast.  Comparison to a neck CT of [**2147-3-23**]. 
FINDINGS:  Images of the brain demonstrate no evidence of mass, mass effect, edema, hemorrhage, or infarction.  There is no abnormal enhancement after contrast administration.  The brain imaging appears normal.  Again identified is opacification of the right mastoid air cells, unchanged since the study of [**2147-3-23**]. 
CONCLUSION:  The brain appears normal.  Again identified is right mastoid opacification.

HISTORY:  Shortness of breath. 
Single portable radiograph of the chest demonstrates abnormal interstitial opacity involving both lungs with mild sparing of the right mid lung.  Trachea is midline and demonstrates a "saber sheath" configuration.  No effusion is detected.  A left-sided PICC line is present with its tip in the SVC.  No pneumothorax.  There is increased airspace opacity superimposed on the abnormal interstitial pattern. 
IMPRESSION: 
Abnormal opacity involving both lungs with relative sparing of the right mid lung.  The findings are better assessed on subsequent CT examination. Diagnostic considerations include both pneumonia and/or pulmonary edema. 
Left-sided PICC line with its tip in the SVC.

INDICATION:  The patient is a 79-year-old male with pelvic hematoma.  Evaluate for pneumothorax or rib fracture. 
EXAMINATION:  PA and lateral chest radiographs. 
COMPARISONS:  CTA from [**2190-3-30**]. 
FINDINGS:  There is chronic hyperinflation of the lungs with interstitial abnormality compatible with chronic pulmonary disease.  There are no focal consolidations concerning for pneumonia.  There are no pleural effusions or pneumothorax.  The cardiomediastinal and hilar contours demonstrate tortuosity of the thoracic aorta.  The patient is status post median sternotomy and CABG. Two rounded nodule-like opacities demonstrated within the lower bases are likely attributed to prominent nipples.  Pulmonary vascularity is normal. There is a small hiatal hernia. 
IMPRESSION:  No acute cardiopulmonary process.

HISTORY:  57-year-old female with acute renal failure. 
COMPARISON:  None. 
FINDINGS:  Transabdominal son[**Name (NI) 211**] images were obtained.  The right kidney measures 12 cm and is normal in echogenicity without focal masses or hydronephrosis.  The left kidney measures 11.1 cm, is also normal in echogenicity without masses, or hydronephrosis.  No stones are seen in either kidney. 
COLOR AND SPECTRAL DOPPLER EVALUATION OF THE KIDNEYS:  Normal arterial upstrokes and diastolic flow is seen throughout the upper, mid and lower poles of the kidneys bilaterally, with normal resistive indices. 
IMPRESSION:  Normal [**Doctor Last Name 34**]-scale, color, and spectral Doppler evaluation of the kidneys bilaterally.

Frontal chest radiograph. 
INDICATION:  Assessment of endotracheal tube, orogastric tube, and central line. 
COMPARISON:  [**2148-11-27**]. 
FINDINGS:  The endotracheal tube is well positioned approximately 5 cm above the carina.  There is a new central line entering via a right IJ access with the tip well positioned in the lower SVC.  An orogastric tube descends the esophagus and is looped within the fundus of the stomach.  The cardiomediastinal silhouette is unremarkable.  There are no focal pulmonary opacifications or pleural effusions.  There is no pneumothorax.  The pulmonary vascularity is normal in appearance. 
IMPRESSION:  Well-positioned endotracheal tube, central line, and orogastric tube.  No evidence of acute cardiopulmonary process.

INDICATION:  Hyperglycemia and elevated white count. 
COMPARISON:  [**2152-11-9**]. 
UPRIGHT AP AND LATERAL VIEWS OF THE CHEST:  Left-sided dual-chamber pacemaker device is noted with leads terminating in the right atrium and right ventricle, unchanged.  The heart size is mildly enlarged with a left ventricular predominance.  The mediastinal and hilar contours are unremarkable.  There are streaky opacities in the lung bases, with mild blunting of the right costophrenic angle suggestive of a small pleural effusion.  No pneumothorax is identified.  There is no pulmonary vascular congestion.  Clips are noted within the right upper quadrant of the abdomen. There are no acute osseous abnormalities. 
IMPRESSION:  Bibasilar streaky opacities likely reflecting areas of atelectasis.  Small right pleural effusion.                                                                       DFDdp

INDICATION: [**Age over 90 **] y/o woman with congestive heart failure exacerbation and atrial fibrillation. ? of extent of CHF, cardiomegaly, or pneumonia. 
COMPARISONS: Upright AP portable chest x ray of [**2128-9-7**]. 
TECHNIQUE: Upright AP portable chest x ray. 
FINDINGS: There is unchanged left ventricular enlargement, and the mediastinal and hilar contours are stable. Since the prior exam, the extent of congestive heart failure has improved with partial clearing of the previously seen diffuse interstitial opacities, as well as a reduction in the degree of upper zone redistribution of the pulmonary vessels. No focal consolidations are seen. There is a small left-sided pleural effusion. 
IMPRESSION: Improvement in degree of congestive heart failure, with no definite evidence of pneumonia.

INDICATION:  A 72-year-old man status post Whipple procedure, now with varicella pneumonia. 
AP SUPINE SINGLE VIEW OF THE CHEST:  omt [**2110-3-15**]. 
FINDINGS:  There is an ET tube in satisfactory position.  There is a right subclavian central line with the tip in the cavoatrial junction.  There is a left subclavian central line with the tip in the lower SVC.  There is a right IJ Swan-Ganz catheter with the tip in the left main pulmonary artery.  There is interval worsening of the diffuse patchy opacities throughout the lungs. This is consistent with worsening pulmonary edema/consolidation.  Persistence of the opacity in the right upper lobe which is unchanged.  No evidence of pneumothorax.  The cardiac, mediastinal and hilar contours are unchanged in appearance. 
IMPRESSION: Interval worsening of bilateral diffuse patchy opacities consistent with worsening pulmonary edema/consolidation.

INDICATION:  Foot pain of the second toe. 
FINDINGS:  3 views of the left foot. 
There is sclerosis of the first MTP joint with no narrowing of the joint space. There is slight osteophyte formation distal first MTP. There are no fractures or dislocations noted and the remaining joint spaces are preserved. On the lateral film, there is a tiny 3mm increased density in the soft tissues at the level of the PIP joints of the phalanges. It is unclear exactly which phalanx this lies inferior to. 
IMPRESSION:   Mild degenerative changes of the first MTP. Tiny density within the soft tissues as described above. This is of unclear clinical significance. If clinically indicated, dedicated views of the second phalanx may be obtained to assess for potential foreign body.

PORTABLE CHEST X-RAY. 
INDICATION:  Post-operative film status post CABG. 
A single AP supine portable radiograph of the chest was obtained at 4:15PM and compared with the pre-operative radiograph from [**2134-11-19**].  Since that film, the patient has been intubated and the endotracheal tube has its tip approximately 2.5 cm above the carina.  There is a Swan-Ganz catheter with tip in the main pulmonary artery.  An NG tube coils back upon itself but tip was probably still located in the upper stomach.  Chest tube and mediastinal drains are noted.  There are bilateral pleural effusions with prominence of the pulmonary vessels in keeping with fluid overload vs. congestive heart failure. 
IMPRESSION:  Position of lines and tubes as described above.  CHF with bilateral pleural effusions.

ABDOMEN 
HISTORY:  Abdominal distention, history of kidney stones. 
COMPARISON:  Abdominal radiograph, [**2096-7-9**]. 
Since the prior study there has been interval development of scoliosis of the lumbar spine with convexity to the left.  There is a 17 mm curvilinear calcification noted to the left of the L3-4 disc space.  Most likely this represents an osteophyte.  There is no subdiaphragmatic free air.  There is a relative paucity of air within the colon.  However air is seen in the rectum and in several loops of small bowel.  No abnormal calcifications to suggest kidney stones are seen. 
IMPRESSION:  Nonspecific bowel gas pattern.

HISTORY:  Status post CABG. 
COMPARISON:  Nine hours prior. 
FINDINGS:  AP supine portable view.  The endotracheal tube terminates in satisfactory position at the thoracic inlet.  The nasogastric tube terminates below the left hemidiaphragm, in the expected location of the stomach.  The right internal jugular Swan-Ganz catheter terminates in the main right pulmonary artery.  There are two left-sided chest tubes and one right-sided chest tube.  The intra-aortic balloon pump terminates 5 cm below the top of the aortic arch. 
The heart and mediastinal contours are within normal limits. There is no pulmonary edema.  There is no pneumothorax or pleural effusion.  There is patchy atelectasis at the right lung base.  There is evidence of median sternotomy. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Satisfactory position of tubes and lines.  No pneumothorax. 2.  Right lung base atelectasis.

INDICATION:  Right olecranon bursitis by physical exam. COMPARISON:  Radiographs of the left elbow dated [**2136-9-5**]. 
These two studies consist of two views of the right and left elbows.  There is mild swelling of the soft tissues overlying the left olecranon, decreased compared to the prior study.  There is soft tissue swelling overlying the right olecranon, greater in extent than compared to the left.  No fractures, dislocations, osseous destructive lesions. There are vascular calcifications which are noteworthy in this age group. 
IMPRESSION:   Presumed bilateral olecranon bursitis, right greater than left (left olecranon bursitis decreased compared to the study of [**2136-9-5**]). Vasculopathy

INDICATION:  Status post ACL reconstruction after patient struck by car. Assess. 
COMPARISON:  Right knee radiographs of [**2129-11-29**]. 
RIGHT KNEE, THREE VIEWS:  The examination was performed with the patient standing.  In the interim since the prior radiograph, there has been an ACL reconstruction with a button and tibial staples in place.  Two suture anchors within the right fibular neck are unchanged from the prior exam.  There is no evidence of hardware complication.  No acute fractures are seen.  There is heterotopic bone about the lateral tibial plateau which is unchanged from the prior exam and relates to remote injury.  No effusion. 
IMPRESSION:  Status post right ACL reconstruction with no evidence of hardware complication.

INDICATION:  History of myocardial infarction, CHF, pneumonia, extubated. Please evaluate nasogastric tube placement. 
Portable AP chest dated [**2198-3-5**] is compared to the prior from yesterday.  The nasogastric tube has been retracted and the tip remains just below the diaphragm.  The side hole of the nasogastric tube is above the gastroesophageal junction.  The heart size is stable.  Again seen are coarse bilateral confluent airspace infiltrates with air bronchograms.  There is no large pleural effusion or pneumothorax. 
IMPRESSION:  Malpositioned nasogastric tube with the sidehole above the gastroesophageal junction. 
COMMENT: These findings were communicated to the clinical team caring for the patient at 9:00 p.m. on [**2198-3-5**] with the instructions to advance the nasogastric tube approximately 10 cm.  Unchanged diffuse bilateral confluent infiltrates.

INDICATION:  History of seizure and pneumonia. 
CHEST AP:  No prior studies are available for comparison. The heart is of normal size. The mediastinal and hilar contours are unremarkable. There is placement of ET tube and NG tube, both of which appear to be in good position. Tip of NG tube is not well visualized.  No evidence of pneumothorax or pleural effusion.  There is no focal consolidation noted.  There is evidence of patchy opacity noted at the right base, consistent with atelectasis vs. pneumonia. Visualized osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION: 
1. Ill-defined opacity at the right base, consistent with atelectasis vs. early focus of pneumonia vs. aspiration.  Followup radiographs may be helpful.

INDICATION:  Ethanol cirrhosis and recurrent upper GI bleed, with elevated WBC.  Question NGT placement. 
TECHNIQUE:  A single portable AP view of the chest is compared with the prior studies from 5 and 7 days ago. 
FINDINGS:  Again seen is a right-sided IJ catheter, terminating in the upper SVC.  Left-sided PICC catheter terminates at the SVC/RA junction, or possibly in the RA.  Dobbhoff tube has been placed, with a coil in the stomach, and the tip still within the stomach.  There is slight increase in bilateral pleural effusions, with a left subpulmonic effusion.  The cardiac silhouette remains enlarged.  There is a persistent appearance of the perihilar haziness. 
IMPRESSION:  Slight increase in bilateral pleural effusions and congestive failure, with Dobbhoff tube tip terminating within the stomach.

REASON FOR EXAMINATION:  Interval change in an intubated patient. 
Portable AP chest radiograph compared to [**2153-10-29**] obtained at midnight. 
The ET tube tip is 3.8 cm above the carina.  The NG tube tip is in the stomach.  The right internal jugular line tip is in low SVC. 
The lung volumes have decreased in the meantime interval.  There is increased crowdness of the vessels accompanied by hilar enlargement which might represent mild pulmonary edema.  There is also increased atelectasis at the left lower lung with partial obscuration of the left hemidiaphragm. 
IMPRESSION:  Standard position of tubes and lines. 
Decreased lung volumes. 
Mild vascular engorgement. 
Worsening of left retrocardiac atelectasis.

INDICATION:  Followup. 
COMPARISON:  [**2188-3-24**]. 
FINDINGS:  In comparison to the previous examination of [**2188-3-24**], the two left-sided chest tubes are in unchanged position.  The overall extent of the left-sided and right-sided pleural effusion has not substantially changed. The extent of retrocardiac atelectasis however has slightly increased.  The size of the cardiac silhouette is unchanged.  No newly appeared pulmonary opacities. 
IMPRESSION:  Unchanged position of left-sided chest tubes.  No pneumothorax. No overall change in the extent of bilateral pleural effusions, slight progression of retrocardiac atelectasis.

DR. [**First Name4 (NamePattern1) 1424**] [**Last Name (NamePattern1) 1425**]

HISTORY:  Myocardial infarction. 
A single portable radiograph of the chest is submitted.  The bilateral costophrenic angles are excluded.  The right lateral hemithorax is excluded. Cardiomediastinal contours are similar to that noted on [**2184-10-9**].  Left thoracic dual-lead cardiac pacemaker and right internal jugular central venous catheter are unchanged.  Increased opacity involving both lungs remain similar in appearance.  Persistent right-sided pleural effusion is similar to that noted previously.  There is mild blunting of the left costophrenic angle. Trachea is midline. 
IMPRESSION: 
Persistent opacities involving the bilateral lungs and persistent bilateral pleural effusions.  Diagnostic considerations again include congestive heart failure.  Pneumonia, particularly involving the left mid lung, is not entirely excluded and attention to this region on followup is recommended.

INDICATIONS:  SOB. Orogastric tube placement. 
PORTABLE AP CHEST: Comparison is made to previous films from  earlier the same day. 
An Orogastric tube is in place and courses below the diaphragm. A endotracheal tube remains in satisfactory position. Cardiac and mediastinal contours are stable. Again demonstrated is a pattern of consolidation within the left lower lobe.  This appears more confluent when compared to the previous study, but direct comparison is somewhat limited due to patient rotation. A small right pleural effusion, versus pleural thickening is noted.  The left costophrenic angle has been excluded from this study and cannot be assessed. 
IMPRESSION: 
1.  Orogastric tube terminates below the diaphragm. 2.  Left lower lobe consolidation, suggestive of pneumonia.

HISTORY:  60-year-old female with multiple surgeries, with ileostomy, now with severe abdominal pain.  Evaluate for obstruction. 
COMPARISON:  [**2112-2-15**]. 
PORTABLE SUPINE AND UPRIGHT ABDOMEN:  Mild gaseous distended loops of small bowel are seen in the lower abdomen, with air-fluid levels and a relative paucity of bowel gas in the remainder of the abdomen. These findings are suggestive of an underlying small bowel obstruction. An ileostomy is present within the right lower quadrant, with surgical staples present. There is no free intraperitoneal air or pneumatosis. Visualized lung bases are clear. Osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION:  Mildly distended small bowel loops, with air-fluid levels, suggestive of a small bowel obstruction.

AP CHEST, 10:16 A.M., [**12-17**] 
HISTORY:  Bronchoscopy evaluate for change. 
IMPRESSION:  AP chest compared to [**12-16**] and 24, 8:35 a.m. 
ET tube and left subclavian line in standard placements.  Nasogastric tube ends in the upper stomach and would need to be advanced 4 cm to move all the side ports beyond the GE junction. 
No pneumothorax.  Small right pleural effusion is probably unchanged. 
Extensive consolidation in the right lung base is more pronounced now than at 3:30 a.m., left lower lobe consolidation is also more pronounced which may represent worsening of either atelectasis or pneumonia.  Dr. [**Last Name (STitle) 53291**] paged.

INDICATION:  Change of neuro status. 
COMPARISON:  [**2134-4-30**], [**2134-4-29**]. 
TECHNIQUE:  CT HEAD WITHOUT IV CONTRAST: 
There is no new hyperdense focus indicative of new hemorrhage.  The previously seen high-density material within the right basal ganglia has now decreased, suggesting continued interval contrast resorption s/p procedure.  Again seen is sulcal effacement in the right parietal lobe posteriorly.  There is increased area of hypodensity along the right frontal lobe and right parietal lobe, suggesting evolving infarct.  There is slight persistent effacement of the right lateral ventricle, but no major midline shift.  The ventricles, sulci and cisterns remain essentially unchanged.  Osseous structures are unchanged. 
IMPRESSION:  No new infarct, although MR is more sensitive at detecting acute stroke.  Continued resorption of extravasated contrast material.  Evolving infarct involving the right MCA territory.

INDICATION:  Follow up status post right femur fracture. 
TECHNIQUE:  Six views of the right femur were compared to radiographs dated [**2150-9-15**]. 
FINDINGS:  A previous screw and plate fixation of the proximal femur has been replaced with an intramedullary rod and gamma nail.  Ghost tracts in the proximal femur are visible.  Callus formation at the proximal femur is present; however, the fracture line remains slightly visible.  Skin staples are seen in the right lateral subcutaneous tissues.  No evidence of hardware failure is seen.  Screw and plate fixation in the proximal tibia has partially imaged.  Degenerative changes of the right knee are present.  Remodeling changes are seen in the right superior and inferior pubic rami compatible with prior fracture. 
IMPRESSION:  Status post placement of intramedullary rod and gamma nail in the right femur.  No evidence of hardware failure.

INDICATION:  To look for pneumothorax and evidence of hematoma. 
TECHNIQUE:  Single AP radiograph of the chest. 
Comparisons with multiple prior radiographs, the most recent from [**2100-8-1**] at 7.39AM. 
FINDINGS: 
LINES AND TUBES:  None. 
LUNGS:  Bilateral pleural effusions and bibasal atelectasis are unchanged. Right suprahilar opacity has resolved suggesting it to be atelectasis previously. No evidence of pneumothorax. 
MEDIASTINUM:  The cardiomediastinal contour is stable. 
BONES:  Patient is status post resection of medial end of clavicle and anterior end of right first rib. 
IMPRESSION: 
Stable bilateral pleural effusion and bibasal atelectasis 
No evidence of pneumothorax.

(REVISED) INDICATION:  78-year-old woman with femoral bruit after cardiac catheterization. 
COMPARISON:  None. 
FINDINGS:  Targeted ultrasound of the right groin area was performed.  On series 1, image 2, the waveform of the common femoral vein appears pulsatile, which was felt to represent adjacent pulsation at the time of the exam as subsequent images 3 and 4 demonstrated normal arterial and venous waveforms. A small amount of hematoma is noted adjacent to the common femoral artery. 
IMPRESSION:  No evidence of pseudoaneurysm.  To completely exclude fistula, a repeat son[**Name (NI) **] is recommended.  Discussed with Dr. [**First Name8 (NamePattern2) 14226**] [**Last Name (NamePattern1) 4045**] in the evening of [**2142-9-30**].

INDICATION:  Pleural effusion, presenting with O2 saturation. 
COMPARISON:  CT chest from earlier the same day at 14:29 hours. 
AP UPRIGHT CHEST:  The heart size is likely normal but obscured by trace effusion. Contour abnormality of the aortic arch consitent with aneurysm .Correlate with  CTA chest for further details. There is a large left pleural effusion with loculated components.  A right pleural effusion, if any, is small.  Left retrocardiac opacification with obscuration of the hemidiaphragm reflects underlying atelectasis/consolidation.  Mild right basilar atelectasis is present.  The pulmonary vasculature is normal. There is no pneumothorax. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Aortic arch contour abnormality consistent with aneurysm. 2.  Small right and moderate left pleural effusion. 3.  Left retrocardiac atelectasis/consolidation.

INDICATION: New feeding tube placement. Hx CABG and hypoxemia. 
CHEST, PORTABLE: 
COMPARISON: AP chest radiograph dated [**2110-12-11**]. 
The heart is mildly enlarged. The mediastinal and hilar contours are stable. There is a mixed alveolar and interstitial pattern throughout both lungs with some areas of lucency within the upper lobe. This likely reflects an element of CHF superimposed on emphysema.  The endotracheal tube is in unchanged position.  The feeding tube tip cannot be seen; the proximal portion of the tip is visible within the upper stomach. 
IMPRESSION: 1. Feeding tube within the stomach. 2. Stable CHF.

INDICATION:  Delayed graft function. 
FINDINGS: 
Comparison is made with the prior study dated [**2121-10-7**].  The transplant kidney measures 11.4 cm in length, without hydronephrosis or perinephric fluid.  There is reversal of diastolic flow within the intrarenal arterial branches, as on the prior study.  Venous flow is identified within the renal veins. 
A tiny punctate echogenic focus is noted within the lower pole, possibly representing a focus of crystals. 
Ultrasound guidance was provided for the nephrology service, for the purpose of transplant biopsy. 
IMPRESSION: 
No change in the reversal of diastolic flow within the arterial branches when compared with the prior study dated [**2121-10-7**].  No hydronephrosis or perinephric fluid. 
Discussed with nephrology service.

PA AND LATERAL CHEST: 
INDICATION:  Status post biventricular RCD with CS lead.  Assess for position. 
Comparison is made to the prior examination of [**2160-7-3**]. 
FINDINGS:  A power pack device is seen in the left upper anterior hemithorax with leads in good position in the right ventricle, right atrium, and tributary of the left coronary sinus.  The cardiomediastinal borders are unchanged.  There are bilateral small pleural effusions, left greater than right as before.  The pulmonary vasculature is normal.  Associated bibasilar compressive atelectasis remains with possible left basilar consolidation. 
IMPRESSION:  Leads in apparent good position.  No cardiac failure.  Stable appearance of bilateral pleural effusions and bibasilar opacities.

ERCP 
INDICATION FOR STUDY:  Liver transplant, hepatitis C, anastomotic stricture. 
Comparison made with prior study from [**2196-6-3**].  Two stents have been inserted to bridge the anastomotic stricture.  The stents are removed and the ducts opacified.  A persistent area of narrowing is noted at the anastomotic site.  The ducts are mildly dilated above the anastomosis.  A balloon was pulled through the area of anastomosis which resulted in slight dilatation at this area.  No extravasation of contrast was noted.  A balloon was also used to inflate the area of the anastomosis.  At the termination of study two stents were left in position bridging the area of narrowing. 
IMPRESSION:  Balloon dilatation of anastomotic stricture following end-to-end biliary anastomosis for liver transplant.

CHEST RADIOGRAPH, AP SEMI-UPRIGHT 
HISTORY:  57-year-old male status post intubation subsequent to PEA arrest. Evaluate interval change. 
FINDINGS:  AP semi-upright chest, comparison study 2:53 a.m., demonstrates interval increase in lung volumes.  Apparent improvement in the bilateral acinar opacities may be secondary to increased volume.  Endotracheal tube is 5.2 cm above carina.  Heart and mediastinal contours are normal.  Costophrenic sulci are sharp.  Multiple bilateral healed rib fractures are again noted. Apical pleural thickening is present. 
IMPRESSION:  Apparent improvement in edema may be due in part to elevated PEEP.

AP CHEST: 
HISTORY:  COPD.  New right subclavian line and dual chamber pacemaker. 
IMPRESSION:  AP chest compared to [**2168-11-6**] and [**2168-11-7**] at 4:31 p.m.: 
Previous large right pleural effusion has almost resolved suggesting resorption of extravasation rather than hemothorax, which would be expected to clear less quickly.  There is no pneumothorax or mediastinal widening.  Right subclavian line and left transvenous right atrial and right ventricular pacer leads are in their expected locations, tracheostomy tube is in standard placement and a nasogastric tube passes below the diaphragm and out of view. There is no pneumothorax or mediastinal widening.  Heart is normal size. Large pulmonary arteries suggest pulmonary arterial hypertension.

INDICATION:  30-year-old woman, with pain on left foot, status post prior tibial and fibular fracture due to trauma. 
COMPARISON:  Prior radiographs of the tibial/fibula from [**2177-5-22**]. 
TECHNIQUE:  Contiguous axial images of the left ankle were obtained with coronal and sagittal reformatted images. 
CT LOWER EXTREMITY, WITHOUT CONTRAST: 
In the distal tibia, the distal aspect of the fixation rod and screw is noted, without evidence of hardware loosening.  The osseous structures are generally markedly osteopenic.  No joint effusion is seen.  No new fractures are identified.  Minimal osteoarthritic changes are seen in the region of the subtalar joint. 
IMPRESSION: 
Patchy osteopenia.  No new fractures or hardware loosening detected.

HISTORY:  Unwitnessed fall from the bed. 
COMPARISON:  None. 
TECHNIQUE:  Non-contrast head CT. 
CT OF THE HEAD WITHOUT CONTRAST:  There is no intracranial mass lesion, hydrocephalus, shift of normally midline structures, major vascular territorial infarct, or intracranial hemorrhage.  Confluent hypodensities within the periventricular white matter consistent with chronic microvascular infarcts.  The [**Doctor Last Name 107**]-white matter differentiation is preserved.  Prominence of the sulci and ventricles consistent with age-related involutional changes. The osseous and soft tissue structures are normal.  The visualized paranasal sinuses demonstrate bilateral air-fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses.  An NG tube is noted. 
IMPRESSION:  No acute intracranial process.

HISTORY:  Laryngeal cancer, rule out recurrent tumor. 
TECHNIQUE:  Axial images of the neck without IV contrast.  No IV was administered due to poor IV access. 
No prior CT's available for comparisons. 
There is evidence of laryngeal resection and a tracheostomy tube.  There is no evidence of obvious recurrence or enlarged lymph nodes, although the evaluation without IV contrast is limited.  If clinically indicated, MRI is suggested.  There are linear opacities in both apices suggestive of dependent atelectases vs. scar.  The visualized osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION:  No evidence of obvious recurrence.  Limited exam due to no IV access.

PORTABLE CHEST of  [**2148-8-8**] 
COMPARISON:  [**2148-8-6**]. 
INDICATION:  Low oxygen saturation.  Evaluate for left lower lobe collapse. 
The exam is limited by flexed position of the patient's neck, resulting in obscuration of the left lung apex at a site of a previously reported pneumothorax.  With this limitation in mind, no definite pneumothorax is identified.  Right internal jugular vascular catheter is unchanged in position.  Nasogastric tube has been removed.  Cardiac and mediastinal contours are stable.  There are worsening hazy and reticular opacities in the mid lung region and lung bases bilaterally, and there is persistent, at least partial atelectasis of the left lower lobe.  Small pleural effusions are again demonstrated. 
IMPRESSION: 
1.  Worsening hazy and reticular opacities likely due to pulmonary edema superimposed upon emphysema. 
2.  Persistent left lower lobe atelectasis and bilateral small effusions.

PA AND LATERAL CHEST: [**2155-3-13**]. 
INDICATION:  Cough and hypernatremia. 
Comparison: CXR [**2155-3-12**]. 
The heart is mildly enlarged.  The pulmonary vasculature is normal.  The thoracic aorta is diffusely calcified and unfolded.  There is minimal bibasilar atelectasis.  The posterior CP angles are blunted representing either tiny bilateral pleural effusions or pleural scarring.  The lungs are otherwise clear.  There is minimal right apical pleural scarring. the pulmonary vasculature is within normal limits.  The mediastinal and hilar contours are normal.  Again seen, is a compression fracture of the 8th vertebra of uncertain chronicity.  There is minimal loss of height of the T4 vertebra which may represent some mild compression as well. 
IMPRESSION:  No evidence of pneumonia.

PA AND LATERAL CHEST, [**2102-4-16**] 
OMPARISON:  [**2102-4-14**]. 
FINDINGS:  Heart size, mediastinal and hilar contours are normal.  Airspace consolidation in the left lower lobe has worsened and is concerning for an evolving pneumonia.
